I now have a complete picture from the knowledge graph. Here is the full diagnosis, root cause, fix, and principle.

---

## Diagnosis

The clip is **not a padding problem** — it's a browser rendering architecture problem. A native `<input>` element clips its text content at the element's **padding edge** using the UA stylesheet's own overflow model. That clipping rect is determined by the platform's native text rendering layer (CoreText on macOS, DirectWrite on Windows), not by CSS layout. At body-copy scale (16–18px) the discrepancy between a font's ascender height and the CSS `line-height` is small enough that the UA padding absorbs it. At display scale (36px+, and especially with IBM Plex Serif which has tall ascenders and deep descenders for a serif face), the ascender of a cap-height glyph like **H, T, I** physically protrudes above the CSS line box by several pixels, and the `<input>`'s internal clip rect cuts them.

Setting `padding-top` does exactly what you observed: it shifts the **content area** down relative to the border box, but the glyph still sits at the top of its **line box**, and the line box still sits flush at the top of the content area. The cap-height still clips. You're enlarging the bucket while the water level stays at the same position inside it.

---

## Root Cause

**AP-064** + **EAP-077** (twin anti-patterns, design and engineering pillars of the same bug).

> **AP-064 — Native `<input>` Text Rendering for Display-Scale Serif Fonts**: The UA hands text layout for `<input>` to the platform's native text pipeline. At display scale with a serif face the native pipeline places glyphs at the typographic baseline and the content box clips anything above the cap-height that exceeds the line box. `padding-top` cannot fix this because it moves the content area, not the glyph's position within the line box.

> **EAP-077 — Assuming CSS Can Fix `<input>` Native Text Clipping for Oversized Serif Fonts**: Any CSS property applied to the `<input>` element itself — `padding`, `line-height`, `height`, `overflow`, `vertical-align` — operates on the box model layer, which is upstream of the platform text renderer. The clip is applied by the renderer, below CSS.

A related secondary trap: **EAP-080 — Adding `overflow: hidden` to Display-Scale Serif Text Without Glyph Padding** — if the wrapper element around the input also carries `overflow: hidden` (common in editors to prevent long titles from breaking layout), it compounds the clip by additionally cropping the rendered text's ink overflow at the container edge.

---

## Fix

The prescribed solution from AP-064 / EAP-077 is to **replace the `<input>` with a `contenteditable="true"` `<div>` (or `<span>`)** for any display-scale serif field. A `contenteditable` element renders through the normal CSS layout pipeline — its text is laid out by the browser's own renderer, not handed off to the platform native text layer — so ascender/descender overflow is honoured by `overflow: visible`, `padding`, and `line-height` the same way they work on any `<p>` or `<h1>`.

### 1. Replace the element in your component

**Before** (`src/components/admin/DisplayTitleInput.tsx` or wherever the field lives):
```tsx
// ❌ Native <input> — text rendering is handed to the platform layer.
// padding-top will never fix cap-height clipping at display scale.
<input
  className={styles.displayTitleInput}
  value={value}
  onChange={(e) => onChange(e.target.value)}
  placeholder="Case study title"
/>
```

**After:**
```tsx
// ✅ contenteditable div — rendered by the browser's own layout engine.
// Ascenders/descenders respect padding and line-height normally.
<div
  ref={editableRef}
  role="textbox"
  aria-multiline="false"
  aria-label="Case study title"
  contentEditable
  suppressContentEditableWarning
  data-placeholder="Case study title"
  className={styles.displayTitleInput}
  onInput={handleInput}
  onKeyDown={handleKeyDown}
  onBlur={handleBlur}
/>
```

Wire the value imperatively — `contenteditable` doesn't take a `value` prop:
```tsx
// Sync external value → DOM only when it differs (avoids cursor-jump on every keystroke)
useEffect(() => {
  const el = editableRef.current;
  if (el && el.innerText !== value) {
    el.innerText = value ?? '';
  }
}, [value]);

function handleInput() {
  onChange(editableRef.current?.innerText ?? '');
}

// Prevent Enter from inserting a <br> / <div> — title is single-line
function handleKeyDown(e: React.KeyboardEvent) {
  if (e.key === 'Enter') {
    e.preventDefault();
    editableRef.current?.blur();
  }
}

function handleBlur() {
  // Trim on commit
  const trimmed = editableRef.current?.innerText.trim() ?? '';
  onChange(trimmed);
}
```

### 2. Fix the SCSS — add glyph-safe padding and neutralise any `overflow: hidden`

**File: `src/components/admin/display-title-input.module.scss`** (or the relevant module):

```scss
// ❌ Before — padding-top combats the symptom, overflow: hidden compounds it
.displayTitleInput {
  font-family: $portfolio-font-serif;
  font-size: $portfolio-type-display;   // e.g. 2.5rem / 40px
  line-height: 1.1;
  padding-top: 12px;                    // doesn't work; makes input taller, not safer
  overflow: hidden;                     // EAP-080: clips ascenders a second time
  white-space: nowrap;
}

// ✅ After — contenteditable + glyph-safe padding formula
.displayTitleInput {
  font-family: $portfolio-font-serif;
  font-size: $portfolio-type-display;
  line-height: 1.2;                     // give glyphs room within the line box itself

  // Glyph-safe padding: at display scale IBM Plex Serif's ascender overshoots
  // the cap-height by ~0.15em. Add that as explicit top/bottom padding so ink
  // never touches the content-area edge.
  padding: 0.2em 0;                     // 0.2em ≈ 8px at 40px — absorbs ascender + descender overshoot

  // NEVER overflow: hidden on a display-scale serif container (EAP-080).
  // Use a clip wrapper outside if you need layout containment.
  overflow: visible;

  // Placeholder via CSS attr() on the data attribute
  &:empty::before {
    content: attr(data-placeholder);
    color: $portfolio-color-text-muted;
    pointer-events: none;
  }

  // Remove contenteditable browser chrome
  outline: none;
  cursor: text;
  white-space: nowrap;
}
```

### 3. If you need layout containment, clip the **wrapper**, not the field

If the parent layout requires overflow containment (e.g. to prevent a long title from overflowing the editor chrome), apply it one level **up** with a calculated safe inset:

```scss
// Wrapper clips layout overflow; the field itself breathes
.displayTitleInputWrapper {
  overflow: hidden;
  // Safe inset: match the field's 0.2em padding so the wrapper's clip edge
  // never coincides with the glyph ink boundary
  padding: 0.2em 0;
}

.displayTitleInput {
  overflow: visible;  // field always visible; wrapper does the containment
  padding: 0;         // padding now lives on the wrapper
}
```

---

## Why `padding-top` Can Never Work — The Structural Difference

This is the key conceptual point you asked about.

```
Native <input> text rendering model
────────────────────────────────────
  ┌── border box ────────────────────────────────┐
  │  padding-top: 12px                           │
  │  ┌── content box ──────────────────────────┐ │
  │  │  ┌── line box ──────────────────────────┤ │
  │  │  │  [platform text renderer places      │ │
  │  │  │   glyph at baseline → cap top sits  │ │
  │  │  │   at line-box top edge]             │ │  ← CLIP applied HERE by UA
  │  │  └─────────────────────────────────────┘ │
  │  └───────────────────────────────────────────┘
  └───────────────────────────────────────────────┘

padding-top moves the content box down inside the border box.
The line box still starts at content-box top.
The glyph still sits at line-box top.
The UA clip still fires at content-box top.
Result: glyph clip moves down with the content box. Cap still clips.
```

```
contenteditable <div> rendering model
──────────────────────────────────────
  ┌── border box ────────────────────────────────┐
  │  padding-top: 0.2em                          │
  │  ┌── content box ──────────────────────────┐ │
  │  │                                         │ │  ← 0.2em breathing room
  │  │  ┌── line box ──────────────────────────┤ │
  │  │  │  [browser layout engine places       │ │
  │  │  │   glyph; ascender ink extends into  │ │
  │  │  │   padding, which is overflow:visible]│ │  ← NO UA clip
  │  │  └─────────────────────────────────────┘ │
  │  └───────────────────────────────────────────┘
  └───────────────────────────────────────────────┘

padding-top creates genuine space above the line box.
overflow: visible lets ascender ink paint into that space.
Result: cap-height fully visible.
```

The structural difference is **who owns the clip**: native `<input>` hands it to the platform renderer (below CSS); `contenteditable` lets CSS own it entirely. At body scale the platform renderer's clip is generous enough to be invisible. At display scale — especially with a face that has tall ascenders like IBM Plex Serif — it surfaces as a hard crop on every cap-height character.

---

## Principle

**AP-064 / EAP-077**: For any field rendered at display scale (`font-size ≥ ~2rem`) with a serif typeface, the correct implementation is a `contenteditable` element, never `<input>`. This is an architectural constraint, not a styling preference — no CSS property written against the `<input>` box model can reach below the UA's text-rendering layer to fix where it places its clip rect.

**EAP-080**: Never apply `overflow: hidden` to an element that directly contains display-scale serif glyphs. If layout containment is required, add it to a wrapper that is offset inward from the glyph ink boundary by at least `0.15–0.2em`.
